          },
          {
            number: 3,
            title: "Write Specific Implementation Intentions for Your Top Three Obstacles",
            description: "Identify the three situations most likely to derail your target behavior — the specific contexts where the old pattern is most strongly triggered. Write a specific if-then implementation intention for each: 'If [obstacle situation], then I will [specific response].' Write these down. Review them weekly. The research effect size for implementation intentions is large enough that this 15-minute exercise may be the highest-ROI intervention in your entire behavior change toolkit. Do not stop at goal intentions — 'I will exercise more' — without writing the specific if-then plans that bridge intention and behavior."
          },
          {
            number: 4,
            title: "Engineer a Reliable Cue-Routine-Reward Loop",
            description: "Identify a reliable, existing cue that will trigger your new behavior — an existing habit, a time of day, a location, or an event that already occurs consistently. Attach the new behavior to this cue. Design the routine to be as simple and frictionless as possible, especially in the early stages — start with a version of the behavior so minimal that skipping it would feel unreasonable. Then identify or engineer a prompt reward that follows the behavior reliably. The reward does not need to be large — the satisfaction of checking a habit tracker, a brief moment of self-acknowledgment, or the natural pleasure of the activity itself can serve this function. Consistency of cue-routine-reward is more important than intensity of any component."
          },
